<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="DIY Spice Blends: Ratios and Recipes" description="Exact ratios for garam masala, za'atar, ras el hanout, cajun, and jerk." canonical="https://28grams.vip/spice-blend-recipes" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>DIY Spice Blends: Ratios and Recipes</h1>
      <p>Exact ratios for garam masala, za'atar, ras el hanout, cajun, and jerk.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Creating your own spice blends ensures maximum freshness and allows you to customize flavor profiles without the added salt and anti-caking agents found in store-bought mixes.</p>
    <h3>Garam Masala (Indian)</h3>
    <p>Toast whole spices first, then grind: 1 tbsp cumin seeds, 1 tsp coriander seeds, 1 tsp cardamom pods, 1 tsp black peppercorns, 1/2 tsp whole cloves, 1 small cinnamon stick, 1/4 of a nutmeg (grated).</p>
    <h3>Za'atar (Middle Eastern)</h3>
    <p>Mix: 2 tbsp dried thyme, 1 tbsp toasted sesame seeds, 1 tbsp sumac, 1/2 tsp kosher salt.</p>
    <h3>Cajun Seasoning (American South)</h3>
    <p>Mix: 2 tbsp smoked paprika, 1 tbsp garlic powder, 1 tbsp onion powder, 1 tbsp black pepper, 1 tbsp cayenne pepper, 1 tbsp dried oregano, 1 tbsp dried thyme.</p>
    <h3>Jerk Seasoning (Caribbean)</h3>
    <p>Mix: 1 tbsp allspice, 1 tbsp brown sugar, 1 tsp garlic powder, 1 tsp cayenne pepper (or scotch bonnet powder), 1/2 tsp cinnamon, 1/2 tsp nutmeg, 1/2 tsp cloves.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>How long do homemade spice blends last?</h3><p>They generally last about 6 months if stored in an airtight container in a cool, dark place. After that, they lose potency.</p><h3>Do I need to toast my spices before blending?</h3><p>Yes, toasting whole spices before grinding and blending them releases their essential oils and significantly deepens the flavor profile of the blend.</p><h3>Can I substitute ground spices for whole spices in a blend?</h3><p>Yes, but the flavor will not be as vibrant. If a recipe calls for whole toasted spices, using pre-ground will result in a flatter taste.</p>
    </div>

